Heat your #oven to 200 degrees. Scrub your @sweet potato{1}(chopped into rough 2cm cubes) but leave the nutritious skin on. Cut the core out of the @yellow pepper{1}, @green pepper{1}, and @red pepper{1} and cut the flesh into 2cm cubes. Peel the @red onion{1} and chop into 2cm cubes. Slice the @red chilli{1/2} in half lengthways and finely chop as much as you dare.

Toss all the vegetables and the chilli in @olive oil{1%tbsp} and @salt{1/2%tsp} and @pepper{1/2%tsp}. Lay out on a #baking tray{} and cook on the top shelf for ~{20-25%minutes}.

Toast off the @walnuts{3} in a dry #frying pan{}. Watch your nuts like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Drain and rinse the @organic lentils{1%small can} thoroughly. Toss the lentils together with the cooked vegetables and @salt{1/4%tsp} and some @pepper{}. Put back in the #oven for a couple of mins for the lentils to warm through. When done add the @red wine vinegar{1%tsp} to the #roasting tray{}.

Crumble the @feta cheese{1} into the medley along with the walnuts and stir through carefully.

Divide your medley between your plates and tuck in.

> OK we admit, 'medley' is a bit of an old-fashioned word, but we weren't quite sure how else to describe this little marriage of deliciousness. The idea was to create something that you could knock up with minimum effort that combined both sweet and earthy flavours. The result was such a corker we've seen it in at least 5 lunch boxes at the Fresh Farm since!